\fs48 The Basics\

\fs28 A+ at times can feel really complicated, but makes complete sense once one learns to understand it. Below is possibly the simplest command.\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 put
\f0 \cf3 \cb1 \
The command put outputs whatever is stored to local storage. To send something to local storage, you use the store command. The store command uses the following syntax:\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 store\cf3  <value>
\f0 \cb1 \
The store command is one of few that take an argument. Almost all commands in A+ use data stored in local storage. The next command is the load command.\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 load\cf3  <variable>
\f0 \cb1 \
On Ag@m OS for UNO, there are only 26 available variables. Each variable can only store an integer. In an interpreter that is not Ag@m OS\'92s A+ Executer, variables can store strings like this:\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 store\cf3  Ima lukewarm bean
\f0 \cb1 \
If it can be converted to a string, it will be converted to a string. To convert it, use any of the following commands:\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 Integer\cb5 \
\cb4 String\cb5 \
\cb4 Float
\f0 \cf3 \cb1 \
The Integer command tries to convert the value in local storage to an integer. The String command tries to convert the value in local storage to a string. The Float command tries to convert the value in local storage to a float.\
If you want to save your changes to the loaded variable, you use the save function.\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 save
\f0 \cf3 \cb5 \
This saves the value in local storage to the loaded variable.\
