\fs48 \cf3 Logic\

\fs28 Logic statements in A+ are really similar to those of other languages, but use the value in local storage rather than a logic equation (var1==var2). Rather than using boolean values, A+ uses 0s and 1s. True = 1. False = 0.\

\f1 \cf2 \cb4 if\cb5 \
\cb4 nif\cb5 \
\cb4 #if \cf3 <value>\cf2 \cb5 \
\cb4 #nif \cf3 <value>\cf2 \cb5 \
\cb4 gt \cf3 <var>\cf2 \cb5 \
\cb4 lt \cf3 <var>
\f0 \cf3 \cb5 \
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\sl264\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf6 \cb7 is \cf3 <var>
\f0 \cb5 \

\f1 \cf6 \cb7 nis \cf3 <var>
\f0 \cb5 \
These logic statements skip the next line depending on the condition.\
The if statement skips the next line of code if the value stored to local storage is equal to 0. It executes the next line otherwise.\
The nif statement is the opposite of the if statement. The difference: executes the next line only if the value of local storage is equal to 0.\
The #if and #nif statements are almost the same as the normal if and nif statements, but the value you give them replaces the 0 in the normal if/nif statements. Rather than only execution if the number is not 0, it only executes if the number is the same as the one given.\
The gt and lt statements are the greater than and less than statements. The gt statement proceeds only if the value of the given variable is larger than the value stored to local storage. The lt statement proceeds only if the value of the given variable is smaller than the value stored to local storage. \
The is statement only executes the next line if the value stored to local storage is equal to the value of the given variable.\
The nis statement only executes the next line if the value stored to local storage is not equal to the value of the given variable.\
\
